# More about lines
In high school our main equation was $y=mx+b$ .
There was also a variation of that: $y-y_{0}=m(x-x_{0})$.
and $y-y_{0}=\frac{y_{1}-y_{0}}{x_{1}-x_{0}}(x-x_{0})$ .
Vertical lines were $x=c$
a nicely combined form was $ax+by=c$. We will call this the "Normal Equation" of a 2D line.
These aren't particularly useful when going to higher dimensions.
### Lines in higher dimensions
![Pasted image 20220110110412.png](data:image/png;base64,)
We call this the vector equation of a line
$$
\boxed {
x = P + t\cdot\vec{v}
}
$$
![Pasted image 20220110111021.png](data:image/png;base64,)
$$
\boxed{
X = (a,b,c) + t \cdot
\begin{bmatrix}A\\B\\C\end{bmatrix}
}
$$
Example:
![Pasted image 20220110110507.png](data:image/png;base64,)
![Pasted image 20220110110947.png](data:image/png;base64,)
We can describe the same line with different values along the same line (such as scaling the vector or choosing another point along the line).

# Normal (Standard) Equation of a Line
Suppose we have $2x+3y=5$
![Pasted image 20220110111838.png](data:image/png;base64,)
for a point to be on the line it has to satisfy this equation.
Generalizing it:
![Pasted image 20220110112102.png](data:image/png;base64,)
We can interpret it as a [[The Dot Product|Dot Product]].
![Pasted image 20220110112246.png](data:image/png;base64,)
Therefore, vector $\begin{bmatrix}a\\b\end{bmatrix}$ is normal to the line.
![Pasted image 20220110112321.png](data:image/png;base64,)

# Computing Distances (2D)
### Distance between a point and a line
Given the line $2x-y=21$. And point $P=(3,5)$.
![Pasted image 20220110113623.png](data:image/png;base64,)
![Pasted image 20220110113804.png](data:image/png;base64,)
![Pasted image 20220110114000.png](data:image/png;base64,)
![Pasted image 20220110114018.png](data:image/png;base64,)

we can then compute distance
![Pasted image 20220110114200.png](data:image/png;base64,)
Generalizing it:
![Pasted image 20220110114624.png](data:image/png;base64,)
![Pasted image 20220110114720.png](data:image/png;base64,)
solving for $t$:
![Pasted image 20220110114807.png](data:image/png;base64,)
![Pasted image 20220110114922.png](data:image/png;base64,)

![Pasted image 20220110115326.png](data:image/png;base64,)

![Pasted image 20220110115501.png](data:image/png;base64,)

dist(P,l)=\boxed{\frac{|ap_{1}+bp_{2}-c|}{\sqrt{a^{2}+b^{2}}}}
$$
